Course Summary

If you're struggling to get ready for the Cambridge Pre-U Mathematics exam, our easy-to-use study guide can help. Work at your own pace as you review our video and text lessons covering all the subjects you'll find on the exam, and then test your knowledge and test preparedness with the multiple-choice quizzes.

About This Course

Preparing for the Cambridge Pre-U Mathematics exam is straightforward and stress free when you use the fun video lessons and corresponding self-assessment quizzes in this course. Each lesson not only covers the knowledge and skills you'll need to prepare for and pass the Cambridge Pre-U Mathematics exam, but also presents the information in a way that's specific to the test. Some of the topics covered include:

  • Quadratic equations and absolute value
  • Polynomials and functions
  • Geometry and circle measurments
  • Trigonometry and trigonometric equations
  • Sequences and series
  • Exponential and logarithmic functions
  • Differential equations, complex numbers and vectors
  • Probability, normal distribution and combinations
  • Kinematics, force, momentum and motion

About the Exam

Many British secondary schools use the Cambridge Pre-U exams with, or in replacement of, the traditional A-level exit exams. Most institutions of higher education accept the Cambridge Pre-U exams for their entrance qualifications. The mathematics exam is split into three sessions, each with two hours allowed for completion. The first two sessions cover pure mathematics, while the third session relates to the application of mathematics.

Cambridge Pre-U Mathematics Registration and Preparation

This study guide prepares you for all areas of the Cambridge Pre-U Mathematics exam. Video lessons cover mathematics topics ranging from quadratic equations to the properties of circles, and you can test your understanding of each lesson with corresponding self-assessment quizzes. Lessons help you review content and learn testing strategies to prepare for the exam.

Schools offering Cambridge Pre-U exams are organized into administrative zones that offer the exams according to timetables. These are linear exams offered at the end of the academic year through institutions of secondary education.

Cambridge Pre-U Mathematics Scoring

The Cambridge Pre-U exams are scored on a nine-grade scale, with three broad categories: distinction, merit and pass. The grades are Distinction 1, 2, and 3, which correspond to a grade of A or A* on the traditional A-levels; Merit 1, 2, and 3, which correspond to the letter grades of B and C on the A-levels; and Pass 1, 2, and 3, which correspond to the A-level letter grades of C, D and E.

Components 1 and 2: Pure Mathematics

Total questions: 80 per component

Time to complete: 2 hours per component

Exam topics covered: Quadratics, algebra, functions, coordinate geometry, circular measure, trigonometry, sequences and series, logarithms and exponentials, differentiation, integration, vector geometry, differential equations, complex numbers, and numerical methods

What you'll learn: This study guide will help you review every area of mathematics covered by the exam, including quadratics, trigonometry, geometry, differential equations, and statistics.

Component 3: Applications of Mathematics

Total questions: 80

Time to complete: 2 hours

Exam topics covered: Probability, data analysis, probability laws, permutations and combinations, discrete random variables, normal distribution, mechanics:, kinematics of motion in a straight line, force and equilibrium, friction, Newton's laws of motion, linear momentum and impulse, motion of a projectile

What you'll study: The chapters of this course cover kinematics, force, laws of motion, equilibrium, momentum, and projectile motion, thoroughly reviewing each topic found on the exam.
